Great way to start the year..I just learned that my painting "Sundance Study" was awarded Honorable Mention in the Plein Air category of the Art Renewal Center's annual salon competition.  I have so much respect for ARC and have participated in the competition for years but this is my first award. There were 5,400 entries this year from 75 countries. Thank you ARC and the judges for this honor and a huge congratulations to all the award winners!

Snow in the sun has got to be one of the most challenging things to paint. No photo can capture the subtleties of all the colors….you just have to get cold to paint snow convincingly. My goal this winter is to paint as many of these small plein airs as possible to try to learn some of the secrets of winter. Winter color notes, 6x12

Anyone who follows me here knows I love animals, but you might not know that I'm a volunteer at the Calaveras Humane Society. This small but mighty organization does so much good for animals in need in our county, adopting out over 500 dogs & cats in 2022 alone.  CHS is having its first ever fundraiser/gala/auction/all around great time this Saturday - tickets to the event sold out long ago, but the auction for my donation will take place here TOMORROW, Friday 3/10. I'm donating a seat in my SOLD OUT online Plein Air From Home Workshop (valued at $595) plus a copy of my video (dvd or streaming, valued at $95). Bidding starts at 8am and closes at 5pmPST. To make it easier to keep track of bids, all bidding must take place on my Instagram post. List your bid in a comment and the highest $$ at 5pm wins. I will contact the winner to arrange payment-  Paypal, Venmo, or CC accepted. 

100% of the final bidding price will go to dogs and cats who will love you for your generosity! Learn to paint and do good at the same time! Tune in tomorrow to bid. And thank you in advance!!😻🐾.
.
.

⁣🎨🌅 "Critiquing is one of the most important things I do as an instructor," said Kathleen Dunphy @kathleendunphyfineart during her special plein air critique session at Plein air live. She added that it's important to remember, however, that an art critique is just an (educated) opinion. She said to take a critique seriously, to listen to it, and then decide what aspects you want to apply to your painting.⠀
⠀
During the session, Kathleen explained that you can think of a subject like cows not as animals, but simply as dark shapes. She used annotated photos to help explain design elements. 🌟⠀
⠀⠀
If you missed the live event, don't worry! You can still access the replays and catch up on all the amazing demos and presentations from top artists in the industry. Don't miss out on this incredible opportunity to learn from the best. 🖌️‍🎨 ⠀⠀

My best wildlife encounters happen when I least expect them to. One morning earlier this summer while I was waiting for a friend to meet me to paint in Point Lobos, I was wandering around the cliffs and taking in the beautiful morning light. As I came around a bend in the path, I was so surprised to discover dozens and dozens of pelicans: flying in, taking off, preening, squawking, fighting, sunbathing, sleeping,… a whole universe of avian activity! And for once in my life, I had my sketchbook and my good camera right there in my hands and could take advantage of this gift from Nature. Many paintings will come from that encounter, including this one: “On the Rocks”, 40 x 60. Swipe to see the finished painting. 
.
.

I think I paint animals just as an excuse to be around them. Here’s a glimpse at my process for creating my latest painting, “Guardian” 18x36: 
All of my animal paintings start with observing the subjects in their natural environment. We have a small herd of goats and two livestock guardian dogs, and there’s nothing I enjoy more than sitting in the pasture with them, sketching and observing their behavior. These are quick gesture drawings in micron pen in my sketchbook, with the goal of just grabbing a pose for as long as they hold it to help me better understand anatomy and movement. I also do quick studies in oil to get more accurate, realistic colors. I take a zillion photos and combine those with my sketches to come up with my designs. I transfer the design to canvas (Senso linen for this painting, which is primed with clear gesso to allow the color of the raw linen to show through) and start painting, using a limited palette of 5 colors + white (you can read about that on my blog on my website). 
The guardian in this painting is Clementine, our incredible Anatolian shepherd. She’s fierce with anything threatening her goats and a total love to me and my husband. This scene came from our daily morning patrol of the pasture, when a sound down by the road got Clem’s attention and fired her up. Not pictured is Hank, her guardian companion, who was undoubtedly charging through the pasture to warn off whatever it was that Clem alerted him to. I love these animals! They are a joy to me and make my life so much richer.
